                <head>155. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>In a February 15, 1962, letter to Chairman <persName corresp="#p_KNS1"
                        >Khrushchev</persName>, President <persName corresp="#p_KJF1"
                        >Kennedy</persName> wrote that he had concluded that negotiations on Berlin
                    would be protracted but believed that, over the longer term, agreement might
                    still be reached. In the meantime, he argued, neither side should undertake any
                    step which could lead to an increase in tensions over Berlin. The President also
                    mentioned the possibility of creating an international commission with East
                    German participation which would supervise access to Berlin. For text, see <ref
                        target="frus1961-63v06#pg_92">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1961–1963, volume VI, pages
                        92</ref>–<ref target="frus1961-63v06#pg_95">95</ref>.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
